You said:
PS D:\Project\jsLearning\Typescript\3_debugging> tsc error TS18003: No inputs were found in config file 'D:/Project/jsLearning/Typescript/3_debugging/tsconfig.json'. Specified 'include' paths were '["**/*"]' and 'exclude' paths were '["D:/Project/jsLearning/Typescript/3_debugging"]'. Found 1 error. my tsconfig.json file: "module": "commonjs", "outDir": "./", /* Specify what module code is generated. */ "rootDir": "./", project folder structure is like this.. 3_debugging folder: script.ts file located
ChatGPT said:

The error message indicates that the TypeScript compiler (tsc) cannot find any input files to process because of the configuration in your tsconfig.json. The issue arises from the include and exclude paths in the configuration file, which are either incorrectly defined or exclude the files you want to compile.

Fixing tsconfig.json

Here’s a corrected version of your tsconfig.json file:

json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "module": "commonjs",
    "outDir": "./dist",  // The compiled files will go into the 'dist' folder
    "rootDir": "./src"   // Specify the source folder for your TypeScript files
  },
  "include": ["src/**/*"], // Include all .ts files in the 'src' folder and its subfolders
  "exclude": ["node_modules"] // Exclude 'node_modules' or any other folder you don't want compiled
}

Suggested Folder Structure

Organize your project folder like this:

scss
3_debugging/
├── src/
│   └── script.ts  // Your TypeScript files go here
├── dist/           // The compiled JavaScript files will be output here
├── tsconfig.json

Steps to Resolve

  1. Move Your script.ts to the src Folder

    • Place your script.ts file inside the src folder.

  2. Compile Your Project

    • Run the following command:
      bash
      tsc
    • This will compile your script.ts file into the dist folder.

  3. Verify the Output

    • Check that the JavaScript file has been generated in the dist folder.

Explanation

  • rootDir: Specifies the root folder for TypeScript source files.
  • outDir: Defines where the compiled JavaScript files are placed.
  • include: Ensures that all .ts files in the specified folder (and subfolders) are included for compilation.
  • exclude: Excludes files or directories that shouldn't be compiled.

If you don't want to use a specific folder structure like src and dist, you can adjust rootDir and outDir accordingly.

You said:
why should i have to create src folder, i want to keep those in root folder
ChatGPT said:

If you want to keep your TypeScript files in the root folder, you don't need to create a separate src folder. You just need to adjust the tsconfig.json settings to work with your current project structure.

Here’s how you can fix it:

Updated tsconfig.json for Files in the Root Folder

json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "module": "commonjs",
    "outDir": "./dist",    // Compiled files go into the 'dist' folder
    "rootDir": "./",       // Treat the root folder as the source folder
    "strict": true         // Optional: Enables all strict type-checking options
  },
  "include": ["*.ts"],     // Include all .ts files in the root folder
  "exclude": ["node_modules", "dist"] // Exclude unnecessary folders
}

Steps to Implement

  1. Keep Your Files in the Root Folder

    • Ensure your script.ts is located in the 3_debugging folder.
    arduino
    3_debugging/
├── script.ts
├── tsconfig.json
├── dist/   // Compiled files will be placed here (created after compilation)

  2. Run the Compiler

    • Use the following command:
      bash
      tsc

  3. Output

    • The compiled script.js will appear in the dist folder.

Explanation of Changes

  • rootDir: "./": Specifies that the root folder is the source folder for TypeScript files.
  • outDir: "./dist": Places compiled JavaScript files in the dist folder to keep your root clean.
  • include: ["*.ts"]: Ensures only .ts files in the root folder are compiled.
  • exclude: ["node_modules", "dist"]: Excludes folders that should not be processed.

This setup keeps everything in the root folder without requiring a separate src folder while ensuring your dist folder is separate for compiled JavaScript files.

You said:
no dist file wanted..
ChatGPT said:

If you don't want a separate dist folder and prefer the compiled JavaScript files to be generated directly in the same folder as the .ts files, you can adjust your tsconfig.json accordingly.

Here’s how:

Updated tsconfig.json

json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "module": "commonjs",
    "rootDir": "./",   // Treat the current folder as the root
    "strict": true,    // Optional: Enables strict type-checking options
    "noEmitOnError": true // Prevents emitting JS files if there are TypeScript errors
  },
  "include": ["*.ts"], // Include all .ts files in the root folder
  "exclude": ["node_modules"] // Exclude unnecessary folders
}

Steps to Follow

  1. Keep Your Files in the Root

    • Ensure your script.ts and tsconfig.json are located in the same folder (3_debugging).
    3_debugging/
├── script.ts
├── tsconfig.json

  2. Compile the TypeScript Files

    • Run the following command:
      bash
      tsc

  3. Output

    • The compiled script.js will be generated directly in the same folder as script.ts.

Explanation of Changes

  • outDir Removed: By not specifying outDir, TypeScript writes the .js files alongside the .ts files.
  • rootDir: "./": Specifies that the root folder is the source folder.
  • noEmitOnError: Ensures no JavaScript files are emitted if there are TypeScript errors.
  • include: ["*.ts"]: Targets .ts files in the root folder.

This setup keeps your folder structure simple, with both .ts and .js files in the same directory.
